Let's see if our next act
is up to the task.

11:46.267 --> 11:47.533
(JAZZ MUSIC)

11:50.567 --> 11:53.300
<i>I'm Greg Wilson,</i>
<i>and, well, I literally grew up</i>

11:53.367 --> 11:55.500
in the world of magic and show business.

11:55.600 --> 12:00.200
<i>My mom and dad were the pioneers of magic</i>
<i>on television back in the 60s and 70s.</i>

12:00.700 --> 12:04.033
<i>And I actually started performing</i>
<i>when I was about six years old on TV.</i>

12:04.100 --> 12:08.133
<i>That was the debut performance of our son,</i>

12:08.233 --> 12:09.267
<i>Greg Wilson.</i>

12:09.500 --> 12:10.800
-(APPLAUSE)
<i>-Thank you very much.</i>

12:10.933 --> 12:14.100
Of course, when I was younger I wanted
to be the cutting edge cool guy

12:14.167 --> 12:15.933
<i>doing all the new, hip, new stuff.</i>

12:16.067 --> 12:19.333
And then I realized that the classics
are really cool.

12:21.900 --> 12:23.800
(LOUNGE MUSIC PLAYING)

12:24.367 --> 12:26.600
I'm taking the older art form of magic

12:26.667 --> 12:28.800
and the older style
of wardrobe and whatnot

12:28.867 --> 12:30.467
<i>and adapting it to the modern audience.</i>

12:31.000 --> 12:32.600
<i>And giving it a little bit of a twist</i>

12:32.967 --> 12:34.333
<i>to make it fun and entertaining.</i>

12:37.100 --> 12:38.433
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

12:41.833 --> 12:45.433
Our next magician is a second
generation performer.

12:45.500 --> 12:48.600
His dad performed in a show called
<i>Magic of Allakazam.</i>

12:48.667 --> 12:51.267
A wonderful place,
which today I believe we call Istanbul.

12:51.333 --> 12:53.767
Will you please welcome
Mr. Greg Wilson.

12:53.933 --> 12:55.467
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

12:59.600 --> 13:00.967
-Hello, Penn.
-How are you?

13:01.033 --> 13:03.400
Hi, Teller. Thank you so much
for having me on the show.

13:03.500 --> 13:06.100
Would you help me out
by personalizing this handkerchief,

13:06.167 --> 13:09.433
by putting your autograph or making
some kind of mark that makes it unique,

13:09.500 --> 13:11.567
one of a kind?
I'll be back and get it in a moment.

13:11.667 --> 13:13.033
-PENN: Okay.
-I'm going to show you

13:13.100 --> 13:14.133
my favorite illusion.

13:14.200 --> 13:15.833
It was created by my father, Mark Wilson.

13:16.200 --> 13:17.767
Let me show you my personal version.

13:18.133 --> 13:19.233
Here we go.

13:19.833 --> 13:20.867
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

15:04.500 --> 15:06.067
May I have the handkerchief?

15:06.233 --> 15:07.300
Thank you so much.

15:08.167 --> 15:09.467
I'll be back.

15:29.900 --> 15:30.967
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

16:14.567 --> 16:15.600
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

16:17.800 --> 16:19.267
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

16:39.533 --> 16:40.667
Wow!

16:41.900 --> 16:43.600
How bout that, ladies and gentlemen?

16:43.667 --> 16:46.367
Wow. Mark, lovely to meet you.

16:46.433 --> 16:48.167
Nani, great, great job.

16:48.233 --> 16:51.100
I saw that when you guys walked
out at the end, which was a lovely end,

16:51.167 --> 16:52.667
Penn and Teller leapt to their feet.

16:52.733 --> 16:54.133
So these guys,
you must have known their work.

16:54.467 --> 16:55.700
Yes, of course.

16:56.067 --> 16:57.267
So fabulous to meet you both.

16:57.333 --> 16:58.867
Ladies and gentlemen, Mark and Nani.

16:58.933 --> 17:00.467
Off you go.
Thank you so much for being here.

17:00.533 --> 17:01.533
How wonderful.

17:03.167 --> 17:04.767
Mark and Nani, ladies and gentlemen.

17:05.166 --> 17:06.599
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

17:07.933 --> 17:10.233
That went good. We were knocked out,
weren't we, by that performance?

17:10.300 --> 17:13.166
The surprise at the end
and then the other surprise.

17:14.400 --> 17:16.300
How wonderful for you to grow up
with your parents doing that,

17:16.367 --> 17:18.666
and then you go into it
on your own as a career.

17:18.733 --> 17:21.532
Was it daunting at all, though, knowing
you were following in their footsteps?

17:21.599 --> 17:22.599
Oh, certainly.

17:22.666 --> 17:26.099
So I would study different types
of magic then my dad was famous for.

17:26.233 --> 17:29.100
So he was famous for doing
card manipulation when he was a kid,

17:29.167 --> 17:31.133
so I studied the balls,
like you saw in the video.

17:31.200 --> 17:33.700
Yeah, yeah. So you would
deliberately mark out your own territory.

17:33.833 --> 17:35.200
I tried.

17:35.333 --> 17:36.500
We're gonna go to Penn and Teller.

17:36.567 --> 17:38.633
What did you think of the act,
and did he fool you?

17:39.167 --> 17:42.833
Well, you know,
50 years ago...

17:44.100 --> 17:46.233
Teller saw that trick

17:46.833 --> 17:49.333
on the <i>Magic Land of Allakazam.</i>

17:50.167 --> 17:52.200
50 years ago he saw that trick.

17:52.300 --> 17:54.633
And 50 years ago,
when he was...

17:55.700 --> 17:57.000
-Young...
-(LAUGHING)

17:58.733 --> 18:02.033
It fooled him absolutely completely.

18:02.900 --> 18:05.200
And there's a few things
that we notice, you know.

18:05.267 --> 18:07.067
When you push a...

18:08.033 --> 18:11.000
Box that's a little bigger
than maybe it needs to be

18:11.100 --> 18:13.933
back against a curtain
that's a little further away

18:14.000 --> 18:16.633
and maybe there's a little extra
time to sign.

18:16.867 --> 18:20.233
And we've done sword boxes before,

18:20.300 --> 18:24.000
and we've seen all sorts of ways
to do sword boxes

18:24.300 --> 18:25.600
and we know...

18:26.433 --> 18:28.533
Lots of ways that people have done tricks

18:28.600 --> 18:30.900
that are slightly inferior to this,

18:31.800 --> 18:33.933
and then at the end of a trick

18:34.233 --> 18:37.467
you produce Mark Wilson

18:38.100 --> 18:39.500
and Nani Darnell,

18:39.767 --> 18:41.600
two of the best magicians

18:41.833 --> 18:43.667
in the United States of America,

18:44.200 --> 18:46.267
and you expect us to say,

18:46.600 --> 18:47.733
that we aren't fooled?

18:48.567 --> 18:50.700
We are not going to do it.

18:51.267 --> 18:53.667
You pull those two people out
of a cabinet,

18:53.733 --> 18:56.133
-you have fooled us.
-Yeah!

18:56.200 --> 18:57.533
No ifs, ands, or buts.

18:57.767 --> 18:59.633
Wow, what a start.

19:00.233 --> 19:01.400
Okay.

19:02.433 --> 19:03.933
Congratulations.

19:07.200 --> 19:08.967
Wow, what a start.
Come on over, Greg.

19:09.033 --> 19:10.533
Wow. Come on over.

19:10.700 --> 19:11.967
But that's not the big prize.

19:12.033 --> 19:15.033
You'll be back here as part of Penn
and Teller's stage show in Vegas.

19:15.100 --> 19:16.167
-So, Greg, congratulations.
-Wow.

19:16.233 --> 19:17.833
Greg Wilson, ladies and gentlemen.

19:18.067 --> 19:19.733
-Fabulous success.
-(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

19:21.967 --> 19:23.433
Okay, off you go, sir.
Congratulations.

19:23.533 --> 19:25.833
Fellows, back to your chairs.
Wow.

19:27.367 --> 19:29.767
Let's meet our next act
and see if they've got what it takes.

19:32.500 --> 19:33.533
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

19:38.333 --> 19:41.167
Hi, my name is Trigg Watson,
and I live in Dallas, Texas.

19:41.333 --> 19:43.800
<i>My dad is a research scientist,</i>
<i>my mom is an editor,</i>

19:43.867 --> 19:44.867
<i>I'm a magician.</i>
<i>Go figure.</i>

19:45.500 --> 19:47.567
<i>In college, I studied business</i>
<i>and theater.</i>

19:47.633 --> 19:48.867
I like to call that show business.

19:49.433 --> 19:51.467
<i>As a performer, I'm inspired</i>
<i>by other art forms,</i>

19:51.967 --> 19:53.667
whether it be theater, music,
even stand-up comedy.

19:54.133 --> 19:56.100
<i>In order to be a good magician,</i>
<i>I love to collaborate with</i>

19:56.167 --> 19:57.233
<i>other experts in other fields</i>

19:57.300 --> 19:58.433
<i>because that gives me new ideas.</i>

19:59.567 --> 20:01.900
<i>While a lot of magicians will</i>
<i>buy magic effects,</i>

20:01.967 --> 20:03.133
<i>I like to build my own.</i>

20:03.300 --> 20:05.900
<i>As technology becomes more and more</i>
<i>integrated with our everyday lives,</i>

20:05.967 --> 20:08.900
<i>I want to create magic with these</i>
<i>everyday technology devices.</i>

20:09.200 --> 20:10.667
So can I fool Penn and Teller?

20:10.933 --> 20:12.267
I'll certainly try my best.

20:12.667 --> 20:14.500
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

20:18.700 --> 20:21.233
If magic doesn't work out
for our next performer,

20:21.300 --> 20:24.567
then he can make a solid living
as a stunt double for Neil Patrick Harris.

20:24.633 --> 20:26.833
Will you please welcome,
Trigg Watson.

20:27.367 --> 20:29.067
-WATSON: Thank you.
-(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

20:30.767 --> 20:32.300
Good evening. Good evening, everyone.

20:32.400 --> 20:33.533
Penn, Teller.

20:33.700 --> 20:35.167
A lot of people think

20:35.333 --> 20:38.867
that magicians on television
use camera tricks.

20:39.200 --> 20:41.200
And in my case, they'd be right.

20:41.767 --> 20:44.200
I'll be performing an illusion
that uses a camera,

20:44.267 --> 20:46.100
or rather, a camera app.

20:46.167 --> 20:47.667
I'm going to go to my tablet here.

20:48.200 --> 20:50.333
Open up my camera app here.

20:50.967 --> 20:53.367
Here we go. Oh, that's Angry Birds.

20:53.633 --> 20:54.833
I was playing that earlier.

20:54.900 --> 20:55.967
Let me get rid of that

20:56.633 --> 20:57.867
and go to the camera app.

20:58.500 --> 20:59.700
There we go. Are you ready?

21:03.333 --> 21:04.400
You know what you call this?

21:05.333 --> 21:06.733
It's an eye pad. Get it.

21:07.133 --> 21:08.333
(LAUGHING)

21:08.433 --> 21:11.000
Came up with that myself.
See, the camera on the back here

21:11.067 --> 21:13.767
is really good about
representing three-dimensional reality

21:13.833 --> 21:15.600
on a two-dimensional screen.

21:15.900 --> 21:18.233
I'd like to try and take
something one step further

21:18.433 --> 21:20.400
by creating something in two dimensions

21:20.467 --> 21:22.533
and then bringing it into real life.

21:23.200 --> 21:24.267
Watch.

21:25.200 --> 21:26.967
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

21:40.667 --> 21:42.300
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

21:49.300 --> 21:52.033
Now of course, I realize that
the screen is a little small,

21:52.100 --> 21:54.767
and I'm going to be doing something
that involves a few more apps.

21:54.833 --> 21:57.167
So fortunately, I came prepared.

21:57.300 --> 22:00.100
I brought along with me
my own personal phone.

22:01.367 --> 22:03.167
(LAUGHING)

22:03.833 --> 22:06.767
Yes, it's a smartphone. It's the 7-plus.

22:07.900 --> 22:10.967
Although, in Penn's hands,
it would be more of a two and a half.

22:12.267 --> 22:14.467
For what I'm about to do,
I require a little bit of assistance,

22:14.533 --> 22:17.133
and I thought who better to help
than our very own host, Mr. Jonathan Ross.

22:17.700 --> 22:19.167
-My pleasure.
-Are you busy? Do you have a minute?

22:19.233 --> 22:21.700
I'm very happy and excited to help.

22:21.767 --> 22:23.000
Come take a seat right here
if you wouldn't mind.

22:23.067 --> 22:24.300
-Sit here?
-Take a seat, yep.

22:24.367 --> 22:25.833
Now, Jonathan, as host of <i>Fool Us,</i>

22:25.900 --> 22:28.767
I know that you've seen
your fair share of card tricks.

22:29.000 --> 22:31.900
So today, we'll be performing
an app trick.

22:32.267 --> 22:34.733
I'm going to select one
of these apps at random

22:34.800 --> 22:37.200
and place it over here
on the microphone stand.

22:37.267 --> 22:39.533
That will serve as my prediction.

22:39.900 --> 22:42.300
Jonathan will then be
choosing a random app

22:42.500 --> 22:45.667
from a similar set of apps right here.

22:46.167 --> 22:49.500
Hopefully, the app that Jonathan
chooses at random

22:49.567 --> 22:51.500
will match my prediction.

22:52.433 --> 22:54.900
Now, if they don't match,
Jonathan messed up.

22:55.133 --> 22:56.400
(LAUGHING)

22:56.633 --> 22:59.300
Now, Jonathan, I don't want
you to see my prediction, all right,

22:59.367 --> 23:01.367
over here on the prediction stand,

23:01.433 --> 23:02.467
so I am going to...

23:02.533 --> 23:03.667
If you don't mind,

23:03.733 --> 23:05.167
I'm going to blindfold you
for the next few minutes.

23:05.233 --> 23:06.900
I have a blindfold for you to wear.

23:07.000 --> 23:09.400
Go ahead and just slip that on for me,
if you wouldn't mind.

23:09.767 --> 23:11.233
I'm open to new experiences.

23:11.700 --> 23:13.033
WATSON: Perfect, there you go.

23:13.167 --> 23:15.833
Jonathan, I want you to know I have
your complete comfort

23:15.900 --> 23:17.200
and customer satisfaction in mind.

23:17.267 --> 23:18.367
Relax, take a break.

23:19.033 --> 23:20.100
-Oh, thank you.
-WATSON: There you go.

23:20.200 --> 23:21.367
Feel free to take a nap.

23:21.467 --> 23:22.800
(LAUGHING)

23:23.667 --> 23:25.067
Time for me to make my prediction.

23:25.733 --> 23:27.233
Let's go with...

23:27.800 --> 23:30.600
Let's see, I think will go
with this one today.

23:31.900 --> 23:33.000
I want everyone to remember it.

23:33.067 --> 23:34.067
Commit it to memory.

23:35.200 --> 23:36.300
I'm going to place it over here

23:37.100 --> 23:38.100
in the stand.

23:39.600 --> 23:41.067
Now, Jonathan...

23:42.433 --> 23:43.633
Is going to be choosing...

23:44.700 --> 23:45.800
A random app

23:46.433 --> 23:49.700
from this set of apps.

23:51.533 --> 23:52.700
(LAUGHING)

23:54.000 --> 23:55.933
All different choices. Jonathan.

23:56.100 --> 23:57.267
Jonathan, you can wake up now.

23:57.333 --> 23:58.567
-Jonathan, wake up.
-It wasn't me.

23:58.633 --> 24:00.167
Welcome back.

24:00.233 --> 24:02.933
Go ahead and remove
your blindfold now, if you don't mind.

24:03.233 --> 24:04.300
-Welcome back.
-Thank you.

24:04.367 --> 24:05.733
Now, Jonathan, I know that

24:05.800 --> 24:07.967
you're probably aware
that some magicians at this point

24:08.033 --> 24:10.100
may try to make you choose a certain card.

24:10.167 --> 24:11.667
You know, try to force you
to make a choice.

24:11.800 --> 24:13.733
I want you to know this is
a completely free choice.

24:13.867 --> 24:16.233
Truly, pick an app, any app.

24:16.300 --> 24:17.933
-Any one of these?
-Just go ahead, reach in there, yep.

24:18.000 --> 24:19.133
Don't look, just take it out.

24:19.400 --> 24:20.433
-This one.
-That one right there.

24:20.500 --> 24:21.733
Now, don't look at it yet,
just take it out.

24:21.800 --> 24:23.600
Perfect. Allow me to recap.

24:23.900 --> 24:25.067
I have chosen one app,

24:25.133 --> 24:27.867
one app only, which has been
resting here on the prediction stand,

24:27.933 --> 24:30.667
chosen from a whole bunch
of different apps on the phone.

24:30.833 --> 24:33.033
Now of course, Jonathan had
a lot of different choices as well.

24:33.100 --> 24:34.500
We've got 24 apps here.

24:34.633 --> 24:37.567
Jonathan, I want you to now say
the name of the app out loud.

24:39.233 --> 24:40.533
Angry Birds.

24:40.600 --> 24:41.733
(LAUGHING)

24:42.300 --> 24:43.467
-Seriously?
-You want to look?

24:43.867 --> 24:44.900
Can I see?

24:46.833 --> 24:47.967
(LAUGHS)

24:49.600 --> 24:50.667
Uh...

24:50.800 --> 24:51.933
Angry Magician.

24:52.100 --> 24:53.900
-(LAUGHING)
-Just...

24:54.967 --> 24:58.933
Just as well, 'cause I may or may not have
chosen Angry Birds as well,

24:59.000 --> 25:00.367
-ladies and gentlemen.
-Wow.

25:00.433 --> 25:01.733
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

25:01.833 --> 25:04.000
You really had me there
for a second, Jonathan.

25:04.067 --> 25:06.100
You really... You really had me.

25:06.200 --> 25:07.867
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

25:12.167 --> 25:13.800
That was good. Thank you, Trigg.

25:13.900 --> 25:15.633
(LAUGHING)

25:15.700 --> 25:16.700
Very good.

25:16.900 --> 25:18.967
Okay, well, let's go front and center here

25:19.133 --> 25:20.267
while Penn and Teller deliberate

25:20.333 --> 25:22.667
and they talk about how you did
what you did and whether they know.

25:23.300 --> 25:25.867
Let me ask you.
I've never met a Trigg before.

25:25.933 --> 25:27.467
Oh, yeah, well, it's...

25:27.600 --> 25:30.767
It's funny, in school,
math was my least favorite subject.

25:30.833 --> 25:32.267
It's a little bit ironic.

25:32.333 --> 25:33.867
But it's a Norwegian name.

25:33.933 --> 25:35.233
So it's your real name,
it's not a nickname.

25:35.300 --> 25:36.433
No, it's literally my real name.

25:36.667 --> 25:37.767
I'll tell you, it's interesting.

25:37.833 --> 25:40.867
The name Trigg in Norse means
trustworthy and truthful,

25:40.933 --> 25:42.367
which is also ironic.

25:42.433 --> 25:43.533
Yeah. (LAUGHS)

25:43.600 --> 25:44.600
Given that I'm a magician.

25:44.667 --> 25:45.800
It's like the path was chosen
for you there.

25:45.867 --> 25:46.867
WATSON: I guess so.

25:46.967 --> 25:48.000
I think they had long enough.

25:48.067 --> 25:49.167
Let's go over now to Penn and Teller.

25:49.233 --> 25:50.367
Why don't we start with you, Penn?

25:50.467 --> 25:51.533
Okay.

25:51.633 --> 25:52.733
(LAUGHING)

25:53.433 --> 25:55.333
Great routine. We love...

25:55.433 --> 25:56.467
Love bringing...

25:56.567 --> 25:57.967
Bringing technology in.

25:58.267 --> 26:02.033
I don't know if you're old enough
or lucky enough

26:02.233 --> 26:03.533
to have met Billy McComb.

26:03.733 --> 26:05.267
Never in person,
but I'm a big fan of his work.

26:05.333 --> 26:06.633
PENN: We were very good friends.

26:06.700 --> 26:08.133
-Terrific.
-Back in the 90s,

26:08.300 --> 26:10.533
we used a thing he did
called the McComb-ical deck,

26:10.667 --> 26:13.033
-which is what you're doing mostly here.
-Yes.

26:13.100 --> 26:15.300
But a very magnetic version of it.

26:15.367 --> 26:17.867
And you did...
The double punch lines

26:17.933 --> 26:19.700
are always great in a magic trick,

26:19.867 --> 26:22.433
to give one punch line
that completely sells it

26:22.500 --> 26:25.033
and then turn it around the other way,
bringing out a failure.

26:25.300 --> 26:27.733
But the thing I liked most about this,
I think,

26:28.000 --> 26:29.800
is the fact that quick-change

26:30.233 --> 26:33.067
is a really, really magical thing

26:33.200 --> 26:36.000
and it's never used enough in magic.

26:36.300 --> 26:39.100
And using a principal of quick-change

26:39.233 --> 26:40.567
in order to do a...

26:40.767 --> 26:43.800
Another punch line on top of it,
was a wonderful thing.

26:43.867 --> 26:45.733
But I think we got all the...

26:45.800 --> 26:47.467
All the details, what you did,

26:47.533 --> 26:51.133
and I like to see it as kind of a tribute
to the great Billy McComb,

26:51.200 --> 26:52.400
who, for those of you who don't know,

26:52.467 --> 26:54.733
is one of the greatest comedy magicians
who ever lived.

26:54.800 --> 26:56.067
-A fabulous guy.
-WATSON: I hope I did him justice.

26:56.133 --> 26:57.133
ROSS: Let me just check.

26:57.400 --> 26:59.133
What Penn said there,
was that enough for you

26:59.200 --> 27:01.533
to accept that they do know
what was going on up here?

27:01.600 --> 27:02.600
-Yes, I think so.
-Okay.

27:02.667 --> 27:04.333
Well, you did it phenomenally.

27:04.933 --> 27:06.267
They know their stuff.

27:06.333 --> 27:07.333
-Thank you, Penn.
-PENN: Thank you.

27:07.400 --> 27:09.667
You were great. It was a great show,
wasn't it, ladies and gentlemen?

27:10.000 --> 27:12.367
Join me in saying thank you
to Trigg Watson.

27:12.433 --> 27:13.900
-Thank you.
-Okay, thank you, sir.

27:13.967 --> 27:15.033
Thank you. I'll have all these.

27:15.100 --> 27:16.633
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

27:17.100 --> 27:19.067
Let's meet our next potential fooler.

27:21.600 --> 27:23.200
Hi, my name is Jen Kramer,

27:23.267 --> 27:26.700
